```

## Alternative Designs

1. _Just call the existing event on a background thread._ This is a very breaking change, since lots of handlers in the wild will depend on the UI thread.
2. _Create a new event like the old one, but continue to use .NET events._ This new pattern allows us to pass in an options during registration so we can add other flags without having to revise the entire API. It also allows for future growth, such as:
   - We could offer overloads that take Func<Args, ValueTask>; we discussed doing this right away now but didn't think we needed it, but it's easy to add later.
   - We can offer overloads that take new kinds of EventArgs. There's a number of problems with our current EventArgs that we've realized over the years and it'd allow a clean swap out to a new model.
   - We can add options for batching, so we aren't dispatching lots of events only for each handler to do it's own batching.
   - If we ever needed to make our WorkspaceChangedImmediate event public, we can do that just by adding another option.
   - The WorkspaceEventRegistration type can offer a WaitUntilAllEventsRaised() so that way code that needs to subscribe to workspace changed and know when you've 'caught up' can do things more cleanly than is done today.

Fundamentally this approach lets us make a clean break from the past while setting us up for long term improvements.

## Risks

The performance benefit here fundamentally requires extensions to move to the new API to get performance benefits. Internally we optimize our code so that if there are no legacy handlers (and no handlers using the MainThread option) we avoid a dispatch to the UI thread, but all it takes is one legacy handler to spoil things.

_This issue has been moved from [a ticket on Developer Community](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/t/The-new-c14-extension-member-function-d/10919273)._

